    <StackPanel xmlns:noesis="clr-namespace:NoesisGUIExtensions"
      x:Name="Infoverlay_HorizontalStack" Margin="32,32,0,0" HorizontalAlignment="Left" VerticalAlignment="Top" Orientation="Horizontal">
      <Component Source="Resources/MiniShowcases/Info_Info_Component.xaml" Height="{Binding Path=ActualHeight, ElementName=TabItem_Off}" Width="{Binding Path=ActualHeight, RelativeSource={RelativeSource Self}}" VerticalAlignment="Top" HorizontalAlignment="Left" d:IsLocked="True"/>
      <TabControl x:Name="Infoverlay_TabControl" Background="{x:Null}" Padding="0,0,0,0">
        <TabControl.MaxWidth>
          <Binding Path="ActualWidth" RelativeSource="{RelativeSource AncestorType={x:Type Page}}">
            <Binding.Converter>
              <noesis:MathConverter Expression="{}{0}/3"/>
            </Binding.Converter>
          </Binding>
        </TabControl.MaxWidth>
        <TabItem x:Name="TabItem_Off" Cursor="Hand" IsSelected="True" Template="{DynamicResource TabItem_Info_Template}" Header="{DynamicResource Info_Off_Geometry}">
          <Grid Background="#FFE5E5E5" d:IsHidden="True"/>
        </TabItem>
        <TabItem x:Name="TabItem_On" Cursor="Hand" Template="{DynamicResource TabItem_Info_Template}" Header="{DynamicResource Info_On_Geometry}">
          <Grid VerticalAlignment="Top" HorizontalAlignment="Left" d:IsLocked="True">
            <Component Source="Resources/MiniShowcases/Info_Overlay_ContentArea_Component.xaml" Text_Title_Str="Data Generation" Text_Description_Str="In addition to its integrated Data import, creation, and management tools, Noesis Studio also offers an incredible embedded Data Generator.
&#x0A;
&#x0A;This feature empowers interface creators to procedurally fill out Data-driven interfaces with randomised, or placeholder content at the click of a button.
&#x0A;
&#x0A;To see the magic of Studio&apos;s Data Generation in action, navigate to the Data Panel [Ctrl+6], and expand the Structure named &apos;DataGeneration_Map_Collection&apos;.
&#x0A;
&#x0A;Hover over the &apos;DataGeneration_Map_Set&apos;, click on the &apos;Generate Sample Data&apos; icon, and watch as a whole new town is generated. (This &apos;Generate Sample Data&apos; action can also be access from the top of the Data Set&apos;s Properties Panel).
&#x0A;
&#x0A;To understand how Data Generation works, you can navigate between the various &apos;DataGeneration_[...]&apos; Data Structures and expand any of the included Properties where you&apos;ll be able to see where the bounds of their Data Generation values are set.
&#x0A;
&#x0A;In this example in particular, you&apos;ll notice how in the &apos;DataGeneration_Map_Plot_Properties` Structure, the &apos;PlotType&apos; is assigned numbers. These numbers are then used as a basis to procedurally switch ContentControl Content Templates in conjunction with Setters inside of the ContentControl itself.
&#x0A;
&#x0A;To see how this works under the hood, right-click on any ContentControl on the map, navigate to &apos;Templates&apos;, then &apos;Content&apos;, and select &apos;Edit Current&apos;. Then, navigate to the Interactivity Panel [Ctrl+3], and within the &apos;Setters&apos; tab. 
&#x0A;
&#x0A;Selecting any Setter in the list will reveal its Properties where its Binding to the Data&apos;s generated number can be exposed. By expanding any Setter, you can then also see how a number change in the Data results in changing to a different DataTemplate (each DataTemplate corresponds to a different building style). These individual buildings can be inspected within the Resources Panel [Ctrl+5]."/>
          </Grid>
        </TabItem>
      </TabControl>
    </StackPanel>
  </Grid>
</Page>
